data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws.** The entire cooperative abort model is gone.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** by the runtime — catching it is dead code.

### Why It Was Removed

`Thread.Abort()` was inherently unsafe — it could interrupt code mid-lock, corrupt shared state, and leave `finally` blocks partially executed. .NET Core replaced it with **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted cooperatively
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful shutdown with a timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — it's still running but
            // there's no safe forced termination in .NET 8.
            // Log a warning; the Task will complete when GetNextItem
            // observes the token or finishes naturally.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O or `Monitor.Wait`, cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** pass the `CancellationToken` into all blocking APIs. |
| **No forced kill equivalent** | There's no safe replacement for `Abort()`. If code doesn't observe the token, it keeps running. Design all blocking paths to accept tokens. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | The original `Thread.Sleep(2000)` blocks the caller. Use `await Task.Delay()` instead. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code** | It compiles but never executes. Replace with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |
| **Filter your catch** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s from inner code. |
| **`IDisposable`** | `CancellationTokenSource` is disposable — leak it and you leak kernel handles. |

### What If `GetNextItem` Can't Accept a Token?

If you're wrapping a legacy blocking API that doesn't support cancellation:

```csharp
// Wrap with a token-aware helper — but the underlying thread still blocks
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    var tcs = new TaskCompletionSource<Item>();
    using var reg = token.Register(() => tcs.TrySetCanceled(token));

    var workerTask = Task.Run(() => tcs.TrySetResult(LegacyBlockingGetNext()));
    return await tcs.Task; // returns on cancel OR completion
}
```

> ⚠️ This unblocks the *caller* on cancellation, but the underlying thread keeps running until `LegacyBlockingGetNext()` returns. This is a **last resort** — prefer refactoring the blocking call to accept a token.
